#!/usr/bin/env python3
# shoemac - a (lovingly fake) Mac OS X Snow Leopard (10.6 / Aqua) desktop drawn
# entirely with foot's vector-graphics protocol, driven by the mouse.
#
#   Run it:   ./bld/debug/foot sh -c 'python3 shoescripts/shoemac'
#   or, installed on PATH inside foot:   shoemac
#
# It's a joke demo, the Aqua cousin of shoexp: an Aurora wallpaper, a
# translucent global menu bar across the top (Apple logo + app menus + live
# clock + Spotlight), a glossy magnifying Dock pinned to the bottom, and a tiny
# window manager with brushed-aluminium windows, traffic-light controls and
# click-to-focus z-order.
#
# All the real apps live in their own shoemac_<name>.py module and register
# through make_app(); the shared Canvas/palette/Pane helpers live in
# shoemac_ui.py.  The four apps are:
#
#   finder    a real-filesystem browser (ports the Entry/Pane scan model)
#   calc      a working clickable calculator
#   about     an "About This Mac" panel
#   safari    a (lovingly fake) web browser with canned pages
#
# Like shoexp, every frame is one comma-delimited DCS drawing program
# (ESC P > g ... ESC \) printed over itself at the home position.  Mouse reports
# arrive as SGR-pixel coordinates that line up 1:1 with the canvas, so a click
# maps straight onto the drawn pixels - windows, dock tiles, lights and all.
#
# Mouse:  click a Dock tile to launch / focus an app;  click Trash for the bin
#         drag a window by its title bar;  click the traffic lights (close /
#         minimise / zoom);  double-click the Macintosh HD icon to open Finder
#         wheel scrolls a scrollable app (Finder)
# Keys:   Esc closes the focused window;  Ctrl-C / q quits (unless a typing app
#         has focus and eats the key)
#
# Env:  SHOEMAC_FORCE=1     draw even if $TERM isn't foot-like
#       SHOEMAC_PLAIN=1     never draw (print a notice and exit)
#       SHOEMAC_SELFTEST=1  render one frame headless and exit (smoke check)
#       SHOEMAC_PIXELFONT=1 render all text with the embedded 8x16 bitmap font
#                           instead of the default antialiased font (set to an
#                           integer >1 to scale the bitmap font, e.g. =2)
#
# Stdlib only; no dependencies.

